	<p>
		<term>Types of radioactivity</term>
	</p>

	<p>
		In this chapter, we’ll be exploring <term>radiation</term> and <term>radioactivity</term>. Radiation is the emission of energy from an object in the form of electromagnetic radiation (which we covered previously) or in the form of parts of atoms. Importantly, radiation doesn’t imply a specific cause for the energy emission. Radioactivity produces radiation, but from a very specific source. In radioactivity, an atom has an unstable nucleus, and that nucleus becomes stable, and in the process releases radiation. There are other sources of radiation other than radioactivity. Radioactivity will always produce radiation.
	</p>

	<p>
		Now that we’ve clarified those two terms, let’s begin to learn about radioactivity in more detail. In the last chapter, we learned about isotopes. To review, isotopes are atoms of an element that have different numbers of neutrons and thus different mass numbers. Some isotopes of atoms are stable, whereas other isotopes have unstable nuclei. These nuclei can stabilize themselves by emitting energy or particles. This is called radioactive decay. Radioactive decay causes that isotope to emit radiation. The radiation that is emitted can be different for different isotopes. forms that we’ll be learning about, because of their relevance to medicine are gamma radiation, beta particles, alpha particles, neutrons, protons, and positrons.
	</p>

	<p>
		What are these different forms of radiation. We’ve previously learned about gamma rays. Gamma rays are a form of electromagnetic radiation or light energy. Out of the different forms of electromagnetic radiation, gamma rays have the highest energies. The other forms of radiation that we’re going to cover are particles. It’s often helpful to group the particles together based on their similarities and differences.
	</p>

	<p>
		Some radioactive isotopes emit <term>gamma radiation</term>. This emission is in the form of a photon (or light) that has energy of a gamma ray. The emission of a gamma ray is caused by an unstable nucleus relaxing to a lower energy state and emitting the lost energy as light. Unlike the other types of radioactive emission, gamma rays are massless and lack charge.
	</p>

	<p>
		Other types of radioactive isotopes decay and emit particles. These types of particles are <term>alpha particles, beta particles, positrons, protons,</term> and <term>neutrons.</term> These particles vary in their mass and charge. Alpha particles have the greatest mass. They are essentially a helium atom nucleus. They consist of 2 protons and 2 neutrons that are fused together into the largest of the particles that we’ll discuss. Beta particles are essentially electrons that are ejected from an atoms as a part of radioactive emission. However, they are ejected from the nucleus rather than from the cloud of electrons around the atom (we’ll discuss how this works more in the next section). Positrons are <term>antimatter</term> particles. They have the same mass as an electron, but they’re positively charged. When antimatter positrons collide with electrons, they <term>annihilate</term> one another and their mass is turned into energy in the form of gamma rays. We’ve already discussed protons and neutrons. Their masses and charges are the same that we’ve previously discussed, even when they are ejected from an atom as a part of radioactive decay.
	</p>

