	<p>
		<term>Balancing decay reactions</term>
	</p>

	<p>
		When radioactive decay occurs, changes happen to the radioactive atom. In most cases, the emission of the radiation results in a change in the nucleus of the atom and can even change one element into another element. To describe the changes that take place after radioactive decay, we can write a radioactive decay equation. The guiding principle when writing a radioactive decay equation is that the total mass and total charge cannot change after the decay has occurred.
	</p>

	<p>
		The first type of decay equation that we’ll explore is gamma decay. Unlike other forms of radioactivity, there is no change in the composition of the nucleus. Instead the nucleus simply changes from a high energy state (called a metastable state) to a low energy state. This makes balancing nuclear decay equations that involve gamma emission very easy. See the example below:
	</p>

	<p>
		<me>_{}^{125}I^{m} \rightarrow \ \gamma +^{125}I</me>
	</p>

	<p>
		In this equation, the superscript m indicates that the nucleus of iodine-125 is metastable (semi-stable/unstable). The Greek letter gamma is used to represent the emitted gamma ray.
	</p>

	<p>
		Two other types of radioactivity (which are quite similar) are beta particles and positrons. Beta particles and positrons are both particles that are emitted from the nucleus. Both of them have mass (although it is very small and often rounded to 0 amu, similar to an electron). Also, both beta particles and positrons have charge; beta particles are negatively charged while positrons are positively charged. When nuclei emit a particle that has charge, the remaining charge in the nucleus has to change; the charge that is emitted has to come from somewhere (it isn’t simply created). <em>This results in the nucleus having the same mass, but a different number of protons.</em> When the number of protons changes, the identity of the atom actually changes from one element to another. See the examples below:
	</p>

	<p><ol>
		<li>
			<p>
				<m>_{1}^{3}H \rightarrow \ _{- 1}^{0}e + \ _{2}^{3}{He}</m>
			</p>
		</li>

		<li>
			<p>
				<m>_{9}^{18}F \rightarrow \ _{+ 1}^{0}e + \ _{8}^{18}O</m>
			</p>
		</li>

	</ol></p>

	<p>
		Equation 1 represents a beta-particle emission. The symbol <m>_{- 1}^{0}e</m> represents the beta-particle and implies that it has 0 mass and an atomic number (or charge, since we’re focusing solely on the nucleus) of -1. Sometimes beta-particles are represented in other ways, such as <m>\beta^{-}\ </m>or <m>e^{-}</m>, but they mean the exact same thing. Equation 2 represents a positron emission with the <m>_{+ 1}^{0}e</m> representing the positron (other times it may be represented by <m>\beta^{+}</m> or <m>e^{+}</m>). Note that in both cases, the identity of the isotope changes after the particle is emitted. <em>This is because nuclear decay equations must balance both charge and mass on both sides of the equation.</em> Since beta-particles and positrons lack mass, the mass number of the resulting isotope remains the same as it was in the beginning (in equation 1 the mass is 3 before and after emission; in equation 2, the mass is 18 before and after emission). Now let’s talk about how we figure out the atomic number of the resulting isotope. First, recall that the atomic number of an atom is ALWAYS the number of protons in the nucleus. Since protons are positively charged, the atomic number also ALWAYS gives us the charge of the nucleus of an atom. So, in equation 1, the nucleus of hydrogen began with a charge of +1. Since a beta particle was emitted, and since it has a charge of -1 then the resulting nucleus must have a charge of +2 (because +2 +(-1)= +1). We can figure this out by making a simple equation that states that the charge on the left equals the charge on the right:
	</p>

	<p>
		<me>1 = x + ( - 1)\ \ \ therefore\ x = 2</me>
	</p>

	<p>
		We can do the same for positron emission in equation 2:
	</p>

	<p>
		<me>9 = x + 1\ \ \ therefore\ x = 8</me>
	</p>

	<p>
		Once we know the atomic number of the resulting isotope (2 or 8 respectively in the examples above), then we can figure out which element they represent (He and O respectively).
	</p>

	<p>
		So how do positron and beta-particle emissions work? How is the number of protons changing? When a beta-particle is emitted, a neutron is actually changing into a beta-particle plus a proton. The negative charge of the beta particle balances out the positive charge of the proton, hence why they both come from a neutral particle. So every time a beta-particle is emitted the mass remains the same (because protons and neutrons have masses of 1 amu), but the number of protons increases by one and the number of neutrons decreases by one. When a positron is emitted, a proton is converted into a neutron and a positron. Thus a proton is lost, and the atomic number decreases by one, but a new neutron appears to preserve the mass.
	</p>

	<p>
		Another type of radioactivity is an alpha particle. Alpha particles have mass and charge, specifically a mass of 4 amu and a charge of +2. They are therefore the same as a helium nucleus. When we are balancing a nuclear decay equation involving alpha particle emission, we need to make sure to balance both mass and charge. See the example below:
	</p>

	<p><ol>
		<li>
			<p>
				<m>_{92}^{238}U \rightarrow \ _{2}^{4}{He^{2 +}} + \ _{90}^{234}{Th}</m>
			</p>
		</li>

	</ol></p>

	<p>
		Note that the mass numbers are balanced on both sides of the reaction arrow as are the atomic numbers (or nuclear charge). The alpha particle is denoted <m>_{2}^{4}{He^{2 +}}</m> in equation 3.
	</p>

	<p>
		Finally, radioactive decay can result in the ejection of protons or neutrons from the nucleus. When a proton decay occurs a <m>_{1}^{1}p</m> particle is ejected. When neutron decay occurs the ejected particle is <m>_{0}^{1}n</m>. The rules for writing the decay equations for other types of particles still applies in these cases. We simply need to ensure that the total nuclear charge is the same on both sides of the equation AND that the mass is the same on both sides of the equation as well.
	</p>

